	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The only things that are analog about the NES are the amplification paths starting at the video DAC and the audio DAC. Failing at Castlevania 3 is unrelated to any difference in these analog stages.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>kyuusaku</b> [ Fri Sep 14, 2012 2:03 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: SNES hardware clones</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The SNES is made of static CMOS logic, the NES is made of dynamic NMOS logic. I think they just did a better job with the SNES lithography, which as static logic is probably less process critical. There's also the issue of external wiring which is simpler on the SNES. Lastly AFAIK there's only one set of cloned SNES chips, the NES dies were cloned at least a handful of times, some more successfully than others.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


